TY  - JOUR
T1  - Discrete Dynamic Programming and Capital Allocation
AU  - Nemhauser, G. L.
AU  - Ullmann, Z.
Y1  - 1969/05/01
PY  - 1969
DA  - 1969/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.15.9.494
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.15.9.494
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 494
EP  - 505
VL  - 15
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Dynamic programming algorithms are developed for optimal capital allocation subject to budget constraints. We extend the work of Weingartner [Weingartner, H. M. 1966. Capital budgeting of interrelated projects: Survey and synthesis. Management Sci. 12(7, March) 485?516.] and Weingartner and Ness [Weingartner, H. M., D. N. Ness. 1967. Methods for the solution of the multi-dimensional 0/1 knapsack problem. Oper. Res. 15(1, January?February) 83?108.] by including multilevel projects, reinvesting returns, borrowing and lending, capital deferrals, and project interactions. We are able to handle dynamic programming models with several state variables because the optimal returns are monotone non-decreasing step functions. Computational experience with a variety of problems is reported.
AB  - Dynamic programming algorithms are developed for optimal capital allocation subject to budget constraints. We extend the work of Weingartner [Weingartner, H. M. 1966. Capital budgeting of interrelated projects: Survey and synthesis. Management Sci. 12(7, March) 485?516.] and Weingartner and Ness [Weingartner, H. M., D. N. Ness. 1967. Methods for the solution of the multi-dimensional 0/1 knapsack problem. Oper. Res. 15(1, January?February) 83?108.] by including multilevel projects, reinvesting returns, borrowing and lending, capital deferrals, and project interactions. We are able to handle dynamic programming models with several state variables because the optimal returns are monotone non-decreasing step functions. Computational experience with a variety of problems is reported.
